Beijing's natural ecology continues to improve to attract more than 500 species of wildlife cities to "settle" -- ScienceDaily
2020-07-26 05: 03: 17 Source: Beijing Youth Daily Author: Wang Sisuo Responsible Editor: Wang Sisuo
The natural ecology of the capital continues to improve to attract wildlife cities to "settle down"
There are more than 500 species of wild animals in Beijing.
This newspaper (reporter Wang Bin) A reporter from Beijing Youth Daily learned from the Municipal Landscape and Greening Bureau that in recent years, with the continuous improvement of the natural ecological environment of the capital, the species and number of wildlife have also continued to increase.
At present, the number of terrestrial spinal wildlife living in Beijing has increased to more than 500 species, including state-level protected animals such as brown horse chicken and black stork, as well as state-level protected animals such as wildebeest, swan, gray crane and mandarin duck.
Whether it is urban forests planted everywhere within the Second Ring or small and micro wetlands embedded between buildings, it not only brings the wild interest of nature to the citizens of the capital, but also attracts wild animals to "settle" in the city.
In the height of summer, the Songshan National Nature Reserve, located in the Yanshan Mountains in the northwest of Yanqing District, is vibrant.
One was playing leisurely by the mountain stream, while two dogs and badgers fought with each other.
In retrospect, a wild boar could not resist the "scratching" on his body and was rubbing hard against the bark of the tree. Hu Qiaoli, director of the Songshan National Nature Reserve Administration, said that by the end of 2019, 178 species of wild animals, including golden eagles, state-level protected animals, spoon chickens and gazelle, lived in this green sea with a total area of more than 6,200 hectares. Nearly one third of the wildlife species in the city could be seen here.
"In Matsuyama, wild animals are the true 'owners', and our staff can only be regarded as the 'bodyguards' of others at best."
Hu Qiaoli said that in order to understand the wildlife situation in the reserve on the ground, more than 30 professional rangers patrol along 16 carefully formulated protection routes every day. There will also be a "big circle" every month, spending a whole day traveling almost all over the reserve.
"During the inspection, it is necessary not only to check and record biodiversity, but also to check the installation of artificial nests, rescue injured wild animals, install field infrared cameras and so on."
More than 200 infrared cameras have been installed in the Songshan National Nature Reserve to record the living conditions of wildlife in the forest.
Hu Qiaoli said that with the continuous enrichment of biodiversity in protected areas in recent years, more and more wild animals have appeared in the camera. Leopard cats, roebuck and pig badgers have become "resident guests", and the "mirror appearance rate" of gazelle, a second-class national protected animal, has become higher and higher.
Zhang Zhiming, Director of Wildlife and Wetland Protection of the Beijing Landscape and Greening Bureau, said that the number of terrestrial spinal wildlife in Beijing has increased from 461 in 1994 to more than 500 now. The species and number of wildlife in Beijing have continued to increase in recent years.
The figure of wildlife in cities is becoming more and more common, which is closely related to the continuous upgrading of urban greening in the capital in recent years.
In particular, the new round of million-acre afforestation construction, which began in 2018, proposed to reshape the urban ecological environment, enhance the ecological function of woodland green space, and highlight the concept of "near nature".
The planning strives to achieve interconnection and interaction with the surrounding green areas, so as to facilitate wildlife to "visit relatives and friends". The trees planted are also honey and food source plants popular with animals.
