Poland to withdraw from European treaty to prevent violence against women
The Polish Ministry of Justice said on Saturday that Poland will take steps next week to withdraw from the European Treaty on the Prevention of Violence against Women.
Poland's right-wing government cabinet said that the treaty requires schools to teach students topics related to gender issues, trampling on the rights of students' parents.
Polish Justice Minister Giobello held a press conference and said that his Ministry of Justice will make a request to the Ministry of Labour and Family on Monday to begin withdrawing from the treaty.
That treaty is also known as the Istanbul Convention.
"The treaty contains elements of what we consider to be harmful morphological nature," Giobello said.
Poland's ruling Law and Justice Party and its ruling coalition partners have a close alliance with the Roman Catholic Church and promote a conservative social agenda.
