Engines may stall FAA urgently orders inspection of 2,000 Boeing airliners - Xinhua
The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) issued an emergency airworthiness order on the 24th, requiring emergency inspection of about 2,000 Boeing 737NG and 737Classic airliners registered in the United States. The reason is that the air check valve of the above-mentioned airliners may cause the engine to stop in the air after corrosion.
The FAA said that so far, it has received four reports of air parking of the engines of 737NG and 737Classic passenger aircraft, so it has made an emergency inspection request. The inspection is aimed at passenger aircraft that have been parked continuously for seven days or more and passenger aircraft that have flown less than 11 times so far after being put back into flight.
The FAA warned that if the stage 5 check valve of all two engines of the airliner is corroded, it may get stuck in the open position, causing the airliner to completely lose power and be unable to restart the engine.
The aviation regulator ordered that once the check valve is found to be corroded, air operators must replace this key component before the airliner is put into service again.
Boeing responded later in the day that the outbreak of the new crown outbreak led to a reduction in travel demand, which led to the mothballing or less use of many passenger aircraft, making "check valves more vulnerable to corrosion".
At the same time, Boeing said that air operators have been advised to inspect the airliners involved in the instructions. If problems are found, Boeing will provide assistance in repairing and replacing check valves.
The Associated Press reported that airliners owned by major US air operators usually fly multiple times in a day, but a large number of airliners were grounded after the outbreak of the new crown outbreak. With the recent slow growth of passenger travel demand, some airliners have been put back into operation.
The FAA did not release details of the four air parking reports.
Alaska Airlines disclosed one of the incidents later on the 24th.
In a statement, the air operator said that one of its airliners was flying from Seattle, Washington, to Austin, Texas, on July 15 when an engine suddenly stalled and the airliner eventually made a successful emergency landing at Austin Airport.
Alaska Airlines said that the engine of the airliner has been replaced and the engines of the six airliners have been inspected in accordance with the instructions of the Federal Aviation Administration.
American Airlines, United Airlines and Southwest Airlines said separately on the 24th that their airliners did not experience engine stalling related to air check valves.
Four jets owned by American Airlines will be inspected, while 28 jets owned by United Airlines will be inspected.
Delta Air Lines said it would inspect 20 of its airliners, but did not say whether there had been engine stalls.
A number of media reports said that the FAA emergency airworthiness directive is another shock to Boeing.
One Boeing 737 MAX each from Indonesia's Lion Air and Ethiopian Airlines crashed in October 2018 and March 2019, respectively, killing a total of 346 people.
This series of passenger aircraft was subsequently grounded worldwide, stopped production in January this year and resumed production in May this year.
FaA Administrator Steve Dixon admitted in June that the FAA "made a mistake" in regulating Boeing with regard to the 737 MAX airliner.
