Is it reasonable for a 3-year-old child to sue the university authorities after he was smashed playing in the college playground and received compensation?
2020-07-26 05: 01: 11 Source: Legal Daily Author: Wang Sisuo Responsible Editor: Wang Sisuo
The playground was smashed, and the child sued the school authorities after receiving compensation.
Zhao Yifan, Correspondent of this newspaper
Xiaowen, 3, was playing in the playground of a university when he was accidentally hit in the head by Chen Mou of the softball team while pitching.
After Chen made compensation, Xiaowen 's father, Mr. Wen, sued the school to the court as Xiaowen' s legal representative, demanding that the school where the playground was located apologize and pay a total of 20,000 yuan for medical expenses and compensation for moral damage.
Recently, after hearing the case, the Haidian District People 's Court of Beijing held that the school had set up a protective net in the playground at the time of the incident, and had fulfilled its appropriate safety and security obligations, and Chen had made compensation. According to the judgment, the plaintiff' s claim was rejected.
Mr. Wen claimed that during the summer vacation of 2019, he took Xiaowen to play in the school playground, when the softball team was training in the playground.
In order to avoid the risks caused by this, Xiaowen, Mr. Wen and many other children and parents are active in the safe area designated by the softball team.
However, after that, Chen Mou, a member of the softball team, got rid of the ball while pitching, causing the softball to fly over the net to the above-mentioned safe area and hit Xiaowen in the back of the head.
Mr. Wen immediately took Xiaowen to the hospital for treatment and was diagnosed with head trauma.
Mr. Wen believed that the facilities of the school stadium did not comply with the relevant safety regulations and did not effectively manage the team and related facilities.
The fault of the school led to the occurrence of the above incident, which led to great physical and mental suffering for Xiaowen, as well as great suffering for his family, for which the school should bear legal responsibility.
In this regard, the school argued that the school had set up a protective net in the playground and posted management regulations and training notices, informing it that it was necessary to maintain a safe distance from the training ground and remind it of its own safety when entering the playground. The plaintiff could not prove that the school had "failed to fulfill its safety and security obligations", so he did not agree to compensation.
After hearing the case, the court held that the venue of the incident was a venue open to the public free of charge by the university involved. Although the school has a safety and security obligation for the management of the playground, this safety and security obligation only needs to meet the general duty of care.
At the time of the incident, the school set up a protective net in the playground and has fulfilled its appropriate safety and security obligations. Chen also compensated Xiaowen for medical expenses, transportation expenses and other losses of more than 2,000 yuan in accordance with the compensation agreement reached before. The two parties agreed to resolve the dispute in one go.
Afterwards, Xiaowen 's parents once again claimed compensation from the school, which was unfounded in the law, and the court ruled against all the plaintiffs' claims.
After the judgment was handed down, neither party appealed, and the judgment has now entered into force.
According to Article 37 of China's Tort Liability Law, schools, as managers of public places, have the obligation of safety and security. In the case of damage caused by the actions of a third party, the third party shall bear the tort liability, while the manager of a public place who fails to fulfill the obligation of safety and security shall bear the corresponding supplementary liability.
According to the judge, because as the manager of a public place, he is most likely to understand the actual situation of the whole place and foresee the dangers and damage that may occur, so he is most likely to take necessary measures to prevent the occurrence of losses or mitigate the degree of damage, and the cost of avoiding and mitigating the occurrence of damage is the lowest, so the law stipulates that he shall assume the corresponding safeguard obligations for engaging in social activities.
In this case, for unspecified entrants in playgrounds open to the public free of charge, the safety and security obligations of schools should be appropriate to the social activities they engage in. In particular, they should mainly take basic safety measures and have the obligation to inform them of hidden dangers.
In judicial practice, it is not appropriate to impose excessive safety and security obligations on the managers of public places.
If the school has adopted the establishment of a protective net and has fulfilled its obligation to inform, it may be concluded that the school is not at fault and should not bear legal responsibility.
In addition, for the infringement of third parties, even if the administrators of public places such as schools fail to fulfill their safety and security obligations, their liability is used as a supplement to damages. According to the newly promulgated Civil Code, the administrators may also recover compensation from third parties after assuming supplementary liability.
Therefore, in such accidents, the victim should not expand the scope of the claim after he has received compensation from the direct infringer.
Today I want to show you the way we make things in the future.
I believe that soon our buildings and machines will be able to assemble themselves, replicate themselves and repair themselves.
