Then in the current manufacturing industry, we have skyscrapers - two and a half years, 500,000 to millions of parts, very complex, using new technologies in steel, concrete and glass.
We have exciting machines that can take us into space - five years, two and a half million parts.
But on the other hand, if you look at natural systems, we have two million types of proteins that can fold in 10,000 nanoseconds, and we can replicate DNA with three billion base pairs in about an hour.
That's the complexity of our natural systems, but they're very efficient, more efficient than anything we build, more complex than anything we can build.
They are more efficient in terms of energy.
They rarely make mistakes.
They can repair themselves and maintain a long life.
There is a super interesting thing about natural systems.
If we can convert that into our built environment, there's a lot of potential in the way we construct things.
I think the key is self-assembly.
If we want to use self-assembly in our own physical environment, I think there are four key factors.
The first is that we need to decode all the complexity of what we are trying to build - that is, our buildings and machines.
We need to decode them into simple sequences - basically the DNA of how our buildings work.
Then we need the programmable part that can accept this sequence and use it for folding or remodeling.
We need some energy to activate so that these parts of us can fold according to the program.
We need some type of error correction redundancy to ensure that what we successfully build is what we want.
