The first two projects are MacroBot and DeciBot.
These projects are large-scale reconfigurable robots - 8-foot-long and 12-foot-long proteins.
They are embedded in mechanical and electrical equipment and sensors.
You need to decode the way you want to fold into a series of angles - negative 120 degrees, negative 120 degrees, 0 degrees, 0 degrees, 120 degrees, negative 120 degrees, this kind of thing; a series of angles, or steering, you can pass this order by wire.
Each unit gets its own message - minus 120, for example. It rotates, checks whether the rotation is in place and then passes the sequence to its neighbor.
There are many outstanding scientists, engineers and designers working on this project.
I think this project really reveals: Is this really scalable?
I mean, many people spent thousands of dollars to build this eight-foot robot.
Can we really expand it? Can we really embed robots in every part?
The next problem is to look at passivity, or passively try to make the reorganization programmable.
But it goes a step further, and it tries to do actual calculations.
Basically, the basic construction module of most calculations, the digital logic gate, is embedded directly into each part.
This is not the door to Africa.
There is a tetrahedron on each door to be used for calculation, and there are two input tetrahedrons.
One of them is input from the user, like you're building bricks.
The other is the input of a brick that was put before coming.
Then it will give the output of three-dimensional space.
That means users stacking bricks the way they want them to.
It is calculated on the basis of what has been done before and your instructions.
Now it's starting to move in a three-dimensional space - up or down.
Looking to the left, the input of [1, 1] is equal to the output of 0, indicating the downward.
On the right, the input of [0, 0] is 1 output, indicating upward.
So what this really means is that our structure now includes the blueprint we want to build.
Therefore, the information about the things you want to build has been fully embedded in it.
This means that we have some form of self-replication.
