Yang Hongnien, founder of the Beijing Philharmonic Choir, died at the age of 86 - CNN
Beijing News (reporter Liu Zhen) On July 26, the Beijing Philharmonic Choir published an obituary. Yang Hongnien, founder of the Beijing Philharmonic Choir, a famous Chinese conductor and music educator, a lifelong academic member of the Central Conservatory of Music and a professor in the command department, died in Beijing at 13: 55 on July 26, 2020 at the age of 86 due to ineffective medical treatment.
The picture is from the official website of the Beijing Philharmonic Choir.
Yang Hongnien was born in 1934, a native of Nanjing, Jiangsu Province, and has loved music since childhood.
In 1951, he was the conductor of the Nanjing People's Radio Choir. In the autumn of 1951, he was admitted to the Music Department of East China Normal University in Shanghai. He studied conducting from Professor Yang Jiaren and German conductor Hitzman. He studied music style and polyphonic style from former Soviet expert Alzamanov.
In 1958, he taught in the Music Department of Beijing Art Normal University. In 1973, he was transferred to the Composites Department and the Command Department of the Central Conservatory of Music.
Yang Hongnien founded the Beijing Philharmonic Choir in 1983.
Over the past 30 years, he has adhered to the tenet of "love and dedication", led this choir to sing all over the world, and won dozens of awards in important competitions at home and abroad.
He has conducted the performances of more than 30 groups, including the Central Orchestra Choir, the Central Ethnic Song and Dance Troupe, the Oriental Song and Dance Troupe and the Shanghai Choir, and held a number of symphony concerts and choral concerts.
