Israel strengthens the prevention and control of repeated outbreaks -- ScienceDaily
2020-07-26 04: 56: 44 Source: Guangming Daily Author: Wang Sisuo Responsible Editor: Wang Sisuo
Israel has strengthened the prevention and control of repeated outbreaks
In the early days of the outbreak of Xincrown Pneumonia, Israel 's prevention and control measures have achieved remarkable results.
However, with the gradual lifting of the ban on prevention and control measures, the number of confirmed cases of newly crowned pneumonia in Israel has increased significantly recently. The Israeli government has taken urgent measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic on many occasions.
On February 28, the first case of newly crowned pneumonia was confirmed in Israel, so that it quickly took the closure of all entry and exit ports, the suspension of non-essential industries, the conversion of schools to online teaching, the restriction of public transport and non-essential social activities, the blockade of cities with serious outbreaks, and the joint maintenance of prevention and control measures by the military and police.
This series of measures quickly achieved positive results. By mid-May, the new confirmed cases of newly crowned pneumonia in Israel had fallen back to single digits on a single day.
With the control of the epidemic, all prevention and control measures in Israel have been fully unsealed. Since June, the number of new diagnoses of Xincrown Pneumonia has gradually rebounded.
In particular, after entering July, the spread of the epidemic has been accelerating.
In recent days, there have been more than 1,500 new cases per day in Israel for eight days. As of July 25, there were 916 new cases on the same day.
As of July 25, there were 59,745 confirmed cases and 448 deaths in Israel.
In the face of the rapid rebound of the epidemic, the Israeli government has repeatedly taken urgent measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic.
On July 6, after the number of confirmed cases exceeded 30,000, the Israeli government closed public entertainment places such as gyms, swimming pools, bars and nightclubs. At the same time, it issued a policy of restricting public transport, stipulating that the maximum number of passengers per bus should not exceed 20.
On the 17th, the government announced a series of new restrictions, including the implementation of "city closure" on weekends, stipulating that "city closure" will be implemented between 17: 00 every Friday and 5: 00 every Sunday.
During this period, people will be able to go out, but places such as shops, shopping malls, barbershops, beauty salons, libraries, zoos, museums, exhibition halls, swimming pools and tourist attractions will be closed, while basic service places such as supermarkets and pharmacies will remain open.
At the same time, gatherings of more than 10 people are prohibited on all dates and time periods. Gyms, studios and other places will be closed. Restaurants and cafes will be prohibited from eating, and only takeaway services will be allowed.
At the same time, the Israeli people have not paid enough attention to the seriousness of the epidemic and have not been able to form joint efforts with the government in combating the epidemic.
After the recurrence of the epidemic in Israel, many people took to the streets to protest and march because the government 's prevention and control measures affected their own economic interests.
On July 11, tens of thousands of people held a demonstration in Tel Aviv, arguing that the anti-epidemic policy affected the economy.
On the evening of the 21st, thousands of protesters gathered in front of the residence of Prime Minister Netanyahu in Jerusalem to protest against the promulgation by Prime Minister Netanyahu of preventive and control measures such as banning restaurants and coffee hall food without giving corresponding compensation.
In addition, many people do not abide by the regulations of wearing masks and maintaining a two-meter safe social distance when outdoor activities. In order to avoid being fined by the police for not wearing masks, many people only wear masks on their chins or hang them on their wrists.
During the repeated epidemic period, the school was a serious disaster area for the spread of the new crown virus. According to a reporter 's recent visit to the kindergarten, neither the teachers nor students of the kindergarten wore masks as required by the government, nor did they maintain a safe social distance of two meters from each other, laying hidden dangers for a large number of teachers and students to be infected with the virus.
Professor Elie Waxman, a member of the expert advisory group of the Israeli National Security Council to combat the epidemic, believed that Israel is moving towards a "dangerous situation", pointing out that the current epidemic prevention and control measures taken by Israel are not enough, and all leisure and recreational places and summer schools should be closed to control the further spread of the epidemic.
Waxman said that Israel lacks an overall plan to combat the epidemic, and the parliament and all government departments should abandon their respective interests as soon as possible, reach an agreement on combating the epidemic, and formulate clear steps that include relevant restrictions in different departments.
