Hulunbel, CNN, July 26 (Reporter Li Aiping) On the evening of July 25, the reporter learned from the Arongqi government of Hulunbuir City, Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region, that four local students died of drowning.
On July 24, at 1550 hours, the Arongqi Public Security Bureau was alerted that six junior high school students had drowned in the area.
After receiving the police, the local police rushed to the scene at the first time and rescued two students on the spot. Afterwards, the local emergency response bureau, the water conservancy bureau and other units arrived at the scene one after another and participated in the rescue throughout the process.
According to the report, more than 80 people, including public security police, forest police, fire control and medical care, were deployed at the rescue site, and three rubber boats were sent to continuously salvage the surrounding waters. Professional rescue teams were hired to arrive at the scene to conduct underwater searches through sonar detection.
Reporters learned that local rescue workers found the first dead student at 0640 hours on July 25, the second dead student at 1130 hours on July 25, the third dead student at 1240 hours on July 25, and the last dead student at 1334 hours on July 25. After the above four were brought ashore, none of them were identified by the local 120 emergency center as having vital signs.
Officials said the drowning was a wake-up call for the whole society.
At present, the relevant local government departments are collating some drowning prevention knowledge and hope that the tragedy will not happen again.
