The article said that in the past decade or so, China has made a lot of investment in domestic research and public health construction, which makes China much more prepared for the new crown than it was for Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome (SARS) that year.
The authors said that at the time of the SARS outbreak in 2002, China was initially ill-prepared, especially the pathogen could not be determined.
When the new crown virus was discovered in December 2019, Chinese scientists were soon able to identify the virus species and shared genome sequencing data with the international community on January 11, 2020.
By the end of January, doctors from mainland China and Hong Kong had clarified the clinical characteristics of the virus and warned the world of the threat of the new crown virus through research papers published in The Lancet.
China has also been at the forefront of vaccine research. Under the declaration of a state of emergency by the state, through close cooperation at home, such research has been carried out very quickly and rigorously. In May and July, the results of the progress made in the early trial of the new crown vaccine developed by China were published in The Lancet, respectively.
China's experience shows that it is very important to invest in the national health and research system and effectively improve laboratory capacity.
This is the basis for the rapid and effective response of the country to health emergencies and global health security.
For other countries, especially low- and middle-income countries, it is very worth learning from and learning from.
In addition, China's experience has proved that on the basis of strong research, it is necessary to have a strong high-level to make correct decisions decisively on the basis of scientific basis, so that the new crown epidemic can be effectively controlled.
The article stressed that the government and its leaders must respect science, understand its value and take action against it in the way that is most beneficial to society.
In the early days of the outbreak, the National Health and Construction Commission of China sent three groups of infectious disease experts to Wuhan to investigate the risk and spread of the new crown virus. Their recommendations provided a basis for the decision to "seal the city" in Wuhan on January 23. When experts raised the necessity and urgency of building a square cabin hospital, the government quickly made a decision and implemented it quickly. At the same time, the broad participation of the community and the masses also made the epidemic quickly and effectively controlled.
At the end of the article, it is stressed that in response to global health emergencies, all countries need to strengthen global cooperation and jointly respond to them.
