At the Balu Zhuokang sentry post, platoon commander Yu Wang and a soldier stood guard on duty.
In this place, where the average annual temperature is more than a dozen degrees below zero, a row of simple barracks stands at the mountain pass. Not far from the barracks, a national flag flutters in the wind. The soldiers stand guard in the wind every day. At the same time, they need to regularly patrol higher elevations.
The soldiers climbed the steep slope of the rocky pile and needed to use their hands and feet.
It was late July, when flowers and plants were lush in low-altitude areas, and in Balu Zhuokang, only the gully behind the barracks had relatively dense green.
Gao Peng, a soldier who has been stationed at the post for six years, pointed to the gully and said that this is their back garden. Only in July and August each year can they see the grass grow slowly. Soon after, it all turns yellow and is covered with snow.
The foot patrol may take about nine hours.
Under the harsh plateau environment, the soldiers stationed here are accompanied by snow-capped mountains and glaciers all year round. They also regularly patrol mountain passes at higher elevations.
A few days ago, a patrol composed of eight soldiers, led by instructor Liang Yi-xin, once again took to the patrol road.
Each soldier carried a weight of about 30 jin and headed for the target point early in the morning.
On the way, a soldier turned against him, and his comrades rushed to the rescue.
In addition to the patrol mission, the soldiers at the Balao Zhuokang sentry post conduct tactical and physical training every day.
Time passes by, altitude is rising, oxygen content is getting lower and lower, and physical strength is constantly overdrawn. These factors test the will of the patrol members.
They clenched their teeth and insisted, crossing several landslides and crossing several urgent and dangerous beaches one after another.
At about 1600 hours, it was lunchtime for the patrol members. They took out their own dry food and sat on the spot at an altitude of more than 5,700 meters. With sleet and snow, they replenished their strength with food.
The soldiers at the Balao Zhuokang sentry post conducted tactical and physical training.
During the break, they will play cards together, and the loser will do push-ups, which can both entertain and exercise his fitness.
After a short rest in the cold wind, they climbed to the target point of the patrol, took out the national flag on the mountain pass and made a solemn oath.
Behind them are snow-capped mountains, and in front of them are dozens of kilometers of no man 's land. They are the safest guardians of the country.
