One winter morning a few years ago, in Johannesburg, South Africa, I was driving to work when I found the city shrouded in haze.
I drive there almost every day, but this time it is very unusual. I have never seen such a scene before.
Johannesburg is famous for its distinctive beautiful skyline, but it was barely visible that morning.
Soon I realized that it was the severe haze caused by air pollution that I saw.
The contrast between the beautiful environment I used to know and the haze shrouded skyline at this moment surges in my heart.
I fear that there is a good chance that the once colourful sunset beauty will be swallowed up by the dark haze.
At that moment, I felt a strong impulse to do something, but I did not know what to do.
All I know is that I cannot just stand idly by like this.
The biggest challenge is that I do not understand environmental science, air quality management, or atmospheric chemistry.
I am a computer engineer, and I am very sure that I cannot solve the problem of air pollution by coding.
(Laughter) In what capacity am I going to address this?
I am just a small man in the city.
In the next few years, I learned a very important lesson. If we want to achieve a better future, we should all take this lesson to heart.
Even if you are not an expert in a particular field, your professional skills may contain ways to solve problems in that field.
Sometimes, the unique perspective you hold can inspire unconventional thinking and thus influence the situation, but you need to be bold in trying.
Only then can you know the result.
What I knew at that time was that if I wanted to try to change, I had to know enough about pollution first, so I became a student again.
I did some basic research and quickly learned that air pollution is the biggest environmental health risk in the world.
Data from the World Health Organization showed that in 2012, almost 14% of deaths worldwide were caused by air pollution in and around households, especially in middle and lower income countries.
The annual mortality rate caused by air pollution is higher than that caused by malaria and AIDS.
In Africa, early deaths caused by unsafe sanitary conditions, or deaths caused by malnutrition among children, appear feeble in the face of air pollution. At the same time, it also brings huge economic costs: According to the statistics of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development, the expenditure of relevant parties exceeded US$400 billion in 2013.
In my work, I explore the scientific and technological frontier achievements of artificial intelligence, including the symbiotic relationship between humans and machines, find a useful foothold and help us make better decisions.
When I think about the issue of air pollution again, on the issue of how to control air pollution, the matter becomes clear. We need to find better ways to make better decisions. Considering that the problem is huge, it is very necessary to work together.
So I decided to meet some people who work in this field.
I began to talk to officials in Johannesburg and other surrounding cities. I also joined the local scientific community. I also made some phone calls to complete strangers but relevant people.
These experiences that I set out to intervene have helped me to understand this issue more deeply.
It also helped me avoid the trap that people in my business sometimes fall into when trying to innovate: To quickly adopt a technology before they have really mastered the problem.
I started thinking, what can I do to improve this?
I began to ask myself how to effectively integrate my knowledge and skills in software engineering and artificial intelligence with the professional skills of the people I contacted.
I want to create an online air quality management platform to reveal future pollution trends and make relevant forecasts to judge possible results.
I am convinced that my idea can become a realistic solution, but it is also faced with uncertainty, and I cannot guarantee that it will succeed.
What I have is a specific set of engineer skills, the skills I have gained from my work. (Laughter) Of course, for people who have been working in the field of air pollution for many years, my skills are completely new.
I came to realize that sometimes a novel perspective, a new skill set, can lead to something remarkable.
Our willpower and imagination are an indicator light that instructs us to cross obstacles and open a new chapter.
After a deeper understanding of the air pollution problem, I found the air pollution data of the past decade or so, as well as the meteorological data of Johannesburg and surrounding areas. After that, I worked with my colleagues in South Africa and China to create the air quality resolution support system and upload it to the cloud.
This software can analyze historical and real-time data to reveal the trend of pollution changes with time and space.
We then used the new machine learning technology to predict the future pollution situation several days in advance.
This means residents can make better decisions about their daily itinerary and where to settle with their families.
We can predict adverse pollution events in advance and define heavy pollution sources, so that relevant authorities can give instructions to adjust their business activities.
Through auxiliary scenario planning, urban planners can also make better decisions on how to expand infrastructure work, such as residential resettlement in industrial zones.
We have established a pilot pilot of the technology, which has been in operation for 120 days and covers the whole of South Africa.
Our expected results have been verified. The forecast data we have shown and the data we have collected in the field have shown a close correlation.
Through our management, we have introduced world-leading cutting-edge instruments to predict atmospheric quality, with a resolution and accuracy that has never been seen before, so that the city I drove into can benefit. At that time, I said to myself, "Something is not right, I have to find a way to do something."
Therefore, the point is: What if I did not thoroughly investigate the problem of air pollution in the first place?
What if instead of paying attention to the environmental situation of the country, I hope that some places and some other people will take care of these things?
What I've learned from this is that when trying to advance a cause we all believe deeply in, it's important to focus on the possibility of success and consider the consequences of inaction.
We should not be distracted by opposition and resistance, it should inspire us to go further.
So no matter where you are in the world, the next time you find that some of your natural curiosity has been aroused, and it is also a matter of your intention, you have some crazy or brave ideas, even if this is not your field of expertise, ask yourself: Why not try it?
Why not go forward and solve the problem? Do your best and in your own way?
You may get unexpected joy.
Thank you all.
(Applause)
