Many people think that driving is something that only those who can see can do.
Until now, it has also been considered an impossible task for blind people to drive a car safely alone.
Hello everyone, my name is Dennis Hong, and we built a car for people with visual impairment problems for the freedom and independence of the blind.
Before I talk about this car for blind people, let me briefly talk about another project I have done called the Urban Challenge of the Advanced Research Projects Agency of the United States Department of Defense.
It's about building a mechanical car that can drive itself.
You press the start button and no longer touch anything. It can also reach its destination completely automatically.
At the 2007 Challenge, our team won US$500,000 to finish third in the competition.
At about that time, the National Association for the Blind, or the Blind Association, challenged the design team about who could design a car that allowed blind people to drive independently and safely.
We felt like we wanted to try it because we felt like, oh, where is this going to be difficult?
We already have an autonomous car.
We just have to let blind people drive in, so that 's not the end of the matter, right?
(Laughter) But we are not reliable in our mistakes.
What the Blind Association wants is not a car that can carry blind people around, but a car that blind people can make choices and drive on their own initiative.
So we had to give up everything we had and start from scratch.
In order to test this crazy idea, we designed a prototype of a small sand truck to test its feasibility.
In the summer of 2009, we invited many blind young people across the country and gave them a second opportunity to use this car for a ride.
It's definitely a cool experience.
But the problem with this car is that its design can only allow blind people to drive in a very limited environment, like a closed parking lot - even on a path made of red traffic cones.
So with this success, we decided to take the important next step and build a real car that can drive on a real road.
So how does it work?
Well, this is a relatively complex system, but let me explain it and simplify it.
We have three phases.
We have the sensing phase, the computing phase and the non-visual interface.
The driver is obviously invisible, so the system must be able to sense the surrounding environment and collect data for the driver.
In this regard, we use the initial metering element.
It measures acceleration, angular acceleration - like the human ear, the inner ear.
I combine this information with the Global Positioning System (GPS) to predict the location of the vehicle.
We also use two cameras to detect the path of driving.
We also use three laser rangefinders.
Laser scanning of the environment to detect obstacles - from the front, the vehicle passing by the rear also has any obstacles that break into the road and any obstacles around the vehicle.
All the huge amount of information is then aggregated into the computer, which will do two things.
First of all, one thing is to process information to understand the surrounding environment - which are driving paths and which are obstacles - and transform this information to the driver.
This system is also very intelligent and can calculate the safest driving path.
We can also issue instructions on how to operate the operating procedures of the vehicle.
But the question is: How can we transmit the information and instructions to the blind man quickly and accurately enough to ensure that he can drive?
To this end, we have designed many different non-visual user interface technologies.
The original 3-D flat sound system, vibration vests, voice-controlled gears, leg straps and even shoes that put pressure on feet.
But today we are talking about three of these non-visual user interface technologies.
The first interface is called the driving handle.
This is a pair of gloves. At the knuckles, it has a vibration element, so that you can transmit instructions on how to drive - direction and amplitude.
Another device is called the speed shock zone.
This car chair - in fact, this is a massage chair.
We take it out, we reorganize the vibration components in different modes. We let them transmit the speed information, but also have instructions on how to use the accelerator and brakes.
Here, you can see how the computer understands the surrounding environment. Because you cannot see the vibration, we actually put a red light-emitting diode on the driver, so he can see what is happening.
This is the sensing data, which is transmitted from the sensor to the computer.
So these two devices, the driving handle and the speed shock band, are very effective.
But the problem is that these are command suggestive devices.
So it's not freedom in the true sense of the word, is it?
The computer tells you how to drive - turn left, turn right, accelerate, brake.
I call this the co-pilot problem.
Therefore, we are avoiding command suggestive devices and paying more attention to information devices.
A typical example of this non-visual information interface is called empty diagrams.
Think of this as a monitor for the blind.
This is a small tabletop with a lot of holes in it, from which compressed air is removed, so that it can be described as a picture.
So even if you are blind and you put your hand on it, you can sense the behavior route and obstacles.
In fact, you can also change the frequency released in the air and possibly the temperature.
This is actually a multi-dimensional user interface.
Here, you can see the cameras on the left and right sides and how the computer parses and transmits this information to the empty map.
In this way, we are showing a simulation program in which a blind man is driving with an empty map.
This program is of great help in training blind drivers and quickly testing different theories based on different kinds of non-visual user interfaces.
That's basically how it works.
But this car is a model car, and it will not be on the road unless it is proved to be as safe to drive as today's cars, or safer to say.
I truly believe it's going to happen.
But can society, and can they, embrace this radical idea?
What are we going to do with insurance?
How will we issue a driver's license?
There are still many different obstacles behind the technical challenge that we need to solve before it truly becomes a reality.
Of course, the main purpose of this project is to design a car driven by blind people.
But potentially more important than this is the huge value contained in the by-products of this project.
A sensor that can be used to see the darkness, rain and fog.
As well as this new type of interface, we can use these technologies to enable them to provide safer vehicles for visual people.
Or for the sake of blind people, household devices - educational facilities, office facilities application services in daily life.
Imagine that blind students can also use these non-visual interfaces to understand and read what their teachers have written when their teachers write notes on the blackboard in class.
This is extremely precious.
Today, what I showed you is only the beginning.
Thank you very much.
(Applause)
