Understand what professional grade difference is before volunteering to fill in -- ScienceDaily
2020-07-27 02: 22: 36 Source: Chongqing Morning Post Author: Yu Xiao Responsible Editor: Yu Xiao
Understand what professional grade difference is before volunteering to fill in
Every year, students or parents volunteer for the college entrance examination because they do not understand the nouns involved in the voluntary filing, which in turn affects the voluntary filing.
This year, five universities, Beijing Jiaotong University, Beijing University of Science and Technology, Beijing University of posts and Telecommunications, Beijing Forestry University and Beijing University of Chemical Technology, jointly issued admission policies for 2020, eliminating professional grade differences.
What does professional grade difference mean and what is the significance in voluntary filing?
There are three ways to allocate professional rules.
Experts reminded that before filling in the volunteer, it is important to read the Admissions Charter of the desired school in detail and understand the admission rules of colleges and universities, including the transfer ratio, the professional allocation rules, etc.
The rules for the allocation of specialties mean that after the transfer of grades in colleges and universities, there are three main ways for the admission of majors: Professional priority, grade priority and professional grade difference.
The specific method used by colleges and universities will be made clear in the Admissions Charter.
However, there are also some colleges and universities whose admission principle is that the total score is preferred, and there is no grade difference between majors.
That is to say, candidates within the scope of admission will be queued according to the total score. When the score does not reach the voluntary admission score line for the first major, it depends on whether the voluntary admission score line for the second major has been reached, and so on until the last professional volunteer is admitted. There is no grade difference between the volunteers for each major.
The so-called "professional grade difference" means that when arranging candidates' majors, institutions determine the admission majors of volunteer candidates for different specialties according to one or more score values published in the admission charter. This score value is the "professional grade difference".
That is, the difference between the scores of institutions when admitting candidates to volunteer for the first major and non-volunteer for the first major, and the grade difference between volunteers for each major, such as 3, 2 and 1, etc.
For example.
It is assumed that Xiaoming, a student, applied for the examination of A colleges and universities and scored 560 points. His professional volunteers are: Computer, international trade, automation, mechanical engineering and e-commerce. The professional admission of A colleges and universities is based on the method of professional grade difference, which is divided into 2, 1, 1 and 0 points.
In the professional allocation, if Xiaoming 's first major volunteer meets the professional admission requirements and his major has a planned balance, Xiaoming will be admitted to the "computer" major. If the computer is not accepted, his score will be subtracted by 2 points. According to the 558 score, he will be ranked with the candidates who volunteered for the "international trade" examination in the first major to determine whether he meets the professional admission conditions. If he still cannot meet the professional admission requirements, the score will be subtracted by 1 point (i.e. 557 points) for the subsequent major.
Different universities have different professional grade differences.
With the popularization of parallel volunteering, many colleges and universities have now eliminated professional grade differences, but some colleges and universities have still retained this method this year. According to the Admissions Charter published by each university, more than 20 universities have set up professional grade differences this year.
For example, Sichuan Agricultural University, Shandong University of Science and Technology, Heilongjiang University of Traditional Chinese Medicine, Jiangsu University of Science and Technology, Jiangxi Normal University, Chengdu Medical College, Northeast Electric Power University, Jimei University, Nanjing Medical University, Nanjing University of Technology, Ningxia University, Shandong University of Technology, China Civil Aviation Flight Institute, etc.
In these colleges and universities, the professional grade difference set up by each university is different.
Some colleges and universities have grade differences in each major. For example, Ningxia University, candidates whose files have been submitted to the university will be admitted in order of scores after being reduced by one point in the order in which candidates fill in professional volunteers.
And some universities have set up different professional grade differences between different specialties.
For example, Jimei University, the total score of professional volunteer grade difference is 4 points, that is, the difference between first professional volunteer and other professional volunteer is 3 points, there is no grade difference between other professional volunteer, which is considered parallel volunteer, and the professional grade difference between other professional volunteer and transfer professional volunteer is 1 point.
When volunteering, candidates and parents must carefully read the admission policy of the reported school to see if there is any professional grade difference and what is the form of the grade difference. While taking full account of the score, they should also rationally analyze the proposed school and major. If the institution explicitly adopts the grade difference method in the admission charter, candidates should pay attention to the gradient between the various specialties and improve the admission chance when choosing the major.
